s grist for popular biography, as fictional TV material) to explore the ways in which the American presidency functions as a “transitional object” that allows the American citizen to meet or discover the president while going about her everyday life. The book argues that it is French theory - primarily Lacanian psychoanalysis and the radical semiotic theories of Jean Baudrillard - that best accounts for American political life today. Through episodes as diverse as Iran Contra, George H. W. Bush vomiting in Japan, the 1992 Republican convention, the failed nomination of Lani Guinier, and the Iraq War, This Is Not a President brilliantly situates our collective investment in American political culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aPopular culturezUnited States. 0aPresidentszUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  a1992.  aAmerican.  aBush.  aContra.  aGuinier.  aIran.  aIraq.  aJapan.  aLani.  aPresident.  aRepublican.  aThis.  aThrough.  aWar.  acollective.  aconvention.  aculture.  adiverse.  aepisodes.  afailed.  ainvestment.  anomination.  apolitical.  asituates.  avomiting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814777312423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814777312/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK